","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hywel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ieuaf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hywel ap Ieuaf of Trefeglwys was born about 1125, in Trefeglwys, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Ieuaf ap Owain Lord of Arwystli, was 31 and his mother, Margaret verch Gruffudd, was 22. He married Mawd verch Ieuan about 1147, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"um 1125–":"umbes 1125–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1108–Female":"1108–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1095–1130":"1095–1130","1105–1165":"1105–1165","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","Abt 1147":"umbes 1147","1095":"1095","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","ABT 1156":"umbes 1156","1156":"1156","1145":"1145","um 1125":"umbes 1125","1108":"1108","Betws-yn-rhos, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Betws-yn-rhos, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Arwestli, Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Talgarth, Trefeglwys, Montgomery, Wales":"Trefeglwys, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"um 1125–":"noin 1125–Kuollut","1125–Ma